    <p> The intensity and magnitude of an earthquake varies from those that canâ€™t be felt to those strong enough to propel people or objects into the air and cause major destruction</p>
    <p> Intensity would measure the amount of shaking caused by an earthquake</p>
    <p> Magnitude scales are used to measure size of earthquakes</p>
    <p> Scales vary from country to country</p>
    <p> Japan has their own magnitude scale for instance that ranges from 0 to 7</p>
    <p> The USGS uses the moment magnitude scale as the Richter scale is now considered outdated.</p>
    <p> The Richter scale ranges from 2.0 to 9.0 and measures the height of a seismic wave</p>
    <p> The moment magnitude scale ranges from -2.0 to 9.9 and measures the total energy released by the earthquake</p>
    <p> The two scales have similar magnitudes from 3.0 to 7.0</p>
    <p> The largest earthquakes that has been measured on a seismograph was 9.5 known as the 1960 Chilean earthquake on May 22,1960</p>
